title: Pt1_Pre_AD101148-6
data_processing: Raw reads in the fastq format were aligned to Human Genome HG19 using the RNAseq STAR aligner version 2.4.0d.
data_processing.1: Mapped reads for each sample were counted for each gene in annotation files TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19.knownGene using the  GenomicFeatures read summarization program
data_processing.2: Raw reads were normalized with regularized-logarithm transformation (rlog function with robust estimation)
data_processing.3: Normalized FPKM (fragments per kilobase per million mapped reads) were obtained using the robust fpkm estimate function of DeSeq2 v1.12.4.
data_processing.4: To refine subsets of immune cells that were present in each sample, cibersort was used to conduct immune de-convolution on the FPKM values of each patient
data_processing.6: Gene IDs in the processed data files are NCBI Entrez Gene IDs.
data_processing.7: Supplementary_files_format_and_content: Row and normalized feature count matrices
data_processing.9: Supplementary_files_format_and_content: BMS038_118Sample.hg19KnownGene.rld.csv.gz: Rlog-transformed values feature counts matrix
data_processing.10: Supplementary_files_format_and_content: BMS038_118Sample.hg19KnownGene.fpkm.csv.gz: Normalized FPKM feature counts matrix

data_processing.2: Raw reads were normalized with regularized-logarithm transformation (rlog function with robust estimation)
data_processing.3: Normalized FPKM (fragments per kilobase per million mapped reads) were obtained using the robust fpkm estimate function of DeSeq2 v1.12.4.
data_processing.4: To refine subsets of immune cells that were present in each sample, cibersort was used to conduct immune de-convolution on the FPKM values of each patient
data_processing.6: Gene IDs in the processed data files are NCBI Entrez Gene IDs.
